issue.title: `ProfileReport` fails when data frame contains date objects
issue.body:
### Current Behaviour

Whenever a DataFrame contains a series of date objects, creating a profile report fails with the following stack trace:

```
File ~/misc/test/env/lib/python3.9/site-packages/ydata_profiling/model/pandas/describe_date_pandas.py:34, in pandas_describe_date_1d(config, series, summary)
     22 """Describe a date series.
     23 
     24 Args:
   (...)
     30     A dict containing calculated series description values.
     31 """
     32 summary.update(
     33     {
---> 34         "min": pd.Timestamp.to_pydatetime(series.min()),
     35         "max": pd.Timestamp.to_pydatetime(series.max()),
     36     }
     37 )
     39 summary["range"] = summary["max"] - summary["min"]

TypeError: descriptor 'to_pydatetime' for 'pandas._libs.tslibs.timestamps._Timestamp' objects doesn't apply to a 'datetime.date' object
```

NB: #1394 mentions the issue, but it is not the main issue.

### Expected Behaviour

The report should be able to handle comparing date objects, and not only datetime objects. We don't always know in advance what columns are in the data. Some of them are also of dtype `object`, so it is tedious to try to convert all dates to datetimes. 

### Data Description

Any column with `datetime.date` objects

### Code that reproduces the bug

```Python
import pandas as pd
from ydata_profiling import ProfileReport
from datetime import date as dt

df = pd.DataFrame({"t": [dt.today(), dt.today()]})
report = ProfileReport(df)
```


### pandas-profiling version

v4.5.1

### Dependencies

```Text
pandas==2.0.3
```


### OS

Tried with macOS and Docker (python:3.9 image)

### Checklist

- [x] There is not yet another bug report for this issue in the [issue tracker](https://github.com/ydataai/pandas-profiling/issues)
- [X] The problem is reproducible from this bug report. [This guide](http://matthewrocklin.com/blog/work/2018/02/28/minimal-bug-reports) can help to craft a minimal bug report.
- [X] The issue has not been resolved by the entries listed under [Common Issues](https://pandas-profiling.ydata.ai/docs/master/pages/support_contrib/common_issues.html).

comment.body:
I'm building a generic "compare datasets" tool for many data scientists to use.  I want to say "point this tool at your data to see what's different."  I want it to be super simple, one line of code, no knowledge required to use. I do not have control over their data; I don't even see it.  Often it's very dirty; sometimes that means columns with the same names and different types.  If the tool crashes in this case, it's not helpful, and people aren't going to use it. 

I know you build your software to high standards, and you'd agree that ideally your software would not outright crash in any case, but handle errors gracefully.  I've shared what looks to me like a bug; I feel the graceful fix is to recognize when columns have incomparable types, note that, and proceed with the comparison.  Then just say in the report that the types were X and Y and so couldn't be compared.  I hope you agree that's reasonable.  Thanks!
